    <h2>What are mechanical keyboards?</h2>
    <p>
        They are keyboards that use an individual spring and switch to register each key input. Common keyboards like Apple's or the typical keyboard at your office uses membrane beneath each key to register the user's
        inputs. Typing enthusiasts and gamers generally prefer mechanical switches, for a variety of reasons, but the most common are because they last longer and have lower latency. Going a step further and building
        a keyboard opens a rabbit hole for endless customization options, as opposed to buying one at Best Buy. This is the reason why there is a huge community of keyboard enthusiasts around the world and conventions.
        To understand mechanical keyboards, knowing the basics of how switches operates is the best first step to take.
    </p>
