    <h2>Switches</h2>
    <p>Switches are the mechanisms under the keycaps that enable users to type better and more precisely. There are three main categories of switches: <b>linear</b>, <b>tactile</b>, and <b>clicky</b>.</p>
    <h3>Linear</h3>
    <p>
        These are smooth and fast. They are the most fluid type of switches and generally the quiest because there is no tactile feedback during a keypress. The drawback is that it is easier to create typos because
        of this lack of feedback. Gamers prefer linears because of the low pre-travel distance and no tactile bump. The most common linear switches are the Cherry MX Reds.
    </p>
    <img src="~/pics/cherryred.jpeg" height="100" />
    <h3>Tactile</h3>
    <p>
        Tactile switches are the awkward middle child. They have a small bump that you can feel while using them, but are quieter and smoother than clicky swithes. Gamers sometimes prefer tactile switches over linears
        because of the small feedback, and typing enthusiasts who want less force and noise will opt for tactiles. The most common tactile switches are the Cherry MX Browns.
    </p>
    <img src="~/pics/cherrybrown.jpeg" height="100" />
    <h3>Clicky</h3>
    <p>
        Clicky switches, the bane of anyone's existence who hates their scratchy and loud noise for every single keystroke. The biggest upside to using clicky switches is that you will have the best typing experience with
        them. The downside is that you cannot type anywhere except at home or a very secluded area, unless you want to annoy everyone. The most common clicky switches are the Cherry MX Blues.
    </p>
    <img src="~/pics/cherryblue.jpeg" height="100" />
